{"term":"1981","caseName":"Loretto v. Teleprompter Manhattan CATV Corporation","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1981/81-244","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 30, 1982","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger8/oral_argument_audio/18047","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear arguments next in Loretto against Teleprompter Manhattan.","start":0,"stop":7.513,"duration":7.51},{"text":"Mr. Gruen, I think you may proceed whenever you're ready.","start":7.513,"stop":72.784,"duration":65.27}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":72.784,"stop":73.876,"duration":1.09},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court:","start":73.876,"stop":76.267,"duration":2.39},{"text":"I'm here to argue for the preservation of one of our subordinate constitutional rights, namely the preservation of property.","start":76.267,"stop":83.67,"duration":7.4},{"text":"That constitutional right existed in its full sanctity--","start":83.67,"stop":88.716,"duration":5.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you conceding that?","start":88.716,"stop":88.949,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--Excuse me, sir?","start":88.949,"stop":90.027,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In that statement are you conceding it's a subordinate right?","start":90.027,"stop":93.479,"duration":3.45},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":93.479,"stop":94.62,"duration":1.14},{"text":"It's not so subordinate that you can't prevail, is that it?","start":94.62,"stop":99.43,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry?","start":99.43,"stop":100.397,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not so subordinate that you can't prevail.","start":100.397,"stop":102.897,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I hope not, sir.","start":102.897,"stop":103.989,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Argument by irony.","start":103.989,"stop":104.895,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"This constitutional right existed in its full sanctity in New York prior to 1973.","start":104.895,"stop":113.251,"duration":8.36},{"text":"At that time Teleprompter and other cable television companies made a practice of seeking owner consent before installing cable television lines and the necessary accompanying equipment.","start":113.251,"stop":130.979,"duration":17.73},{"text":"It was their practice, dictated by management, to solicit consent using a printed form which you'll find in the joint appendix at pages 32 to 33, which provided specifically for compensation at the rate of five percent of gross revenues derived from the building on which the installation was made.","start":130.979,"stop":153.829,"duration":22.85},{"text":"Effective as of January 1, 1973, Executive Law Section 828 was adopted and made effective in New York, prohibiting landlord interference with installations and prohibiting any payments to landlords from cable television companies or from tenants with respect to such installations, with the exception of purely discretionary compensation which could be made by the cable television commission with respect to installations servicing the tenants on the property on which the installation was made, and then only if application was made for it within a very short period after the installation had been made, some, I believe, 180 days if I remember correctly.","start":153.829,"stop":207.729,"duration":53.9},{"text":"This--","start":207.729,"stop":209.291,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The crossovers aren't even subject to that, are they?","start":209.291,"stop":212.04,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's right.","start":212.04,"stop":212.602,"duration":0.56},{"text":"According to the Court of Appeals, there may be no compensation for crossovers under any circumstances.","start":212.602,"stop":220.537,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Mrs. Loretto then brought this action sounding in trespass, and the sole defense remaining after the elimination of a number of defenses by the Court of Appeals is Section 828, and we're presented therefore with the question of whether there are any extraordinary factors which take this case out of the usual rule that a landlord is entitled to exclusive possession, and particularly to exclusivity with respect to the installation of permanent installations on the property, particularly including television aerials and the like.","start":220.537,"stop":262.192,"duration":41.66},{"text":"We have urged throughout this case the observance of a per se or absolute rule--","start":262.192,"stop":269.909,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, Mr. Gruen.","start":269.909,"stop":271.11,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Justice Brennan.","start":271.11,"stop":272.079,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no distinction made between commercial and residential property?","start":272.079,"stop":274.515,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"No distinction was made between commercial and residential property, that's correct.","start":274.515,"stop":279.28,"duration":4.76},{"text":"The Court of Appeals referred to rental properties in general.","start":279.28,"stop":283.355,"duration":4.08},{"text":"I suppose at some point there may be some fine tuning on that, but that's how it stands.","start":283.355,"stop":289.415,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But there was no commercial property issue presented by the record in this case, was there?","start":289.415,"stop":295.022,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the designated class is the owners of property in New York State on which Teleprompter has made installations.","start":295.022,"stop":307.533,"duration":12.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that class perfected?","start":307.533,"stop":308.799,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Not by the giving of notice, but it has been certified by the Supreme Court, that is to say the trial level court in New York, as consisting of all owners of property in the state on which installations have been made, with a minor exception which I don't think we need to go into here.","start":308.799,"stop":328.355,"duration":19.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, who are they?","start":328.355,"stop":328.62,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Who are all of these?","start":328.62,"stop":330.852,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Who are they?","start":330.852,"stop":331.243,"duration":0.39},{"text":"I think the question is, are there any owners of commercial... non-rental commercial property included in that class?","start":331.243,"stop":338.038,"duration":6.8},{"text":"Do you know?","start":338.038,"stop":339.74,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not know as to non-rental, although I can say that the city license obliges Teleprompter to service hospitals, which would normally be non-rental commercial facilities.","start":339.74,"stop":354.265,"duration":14.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How about just a warehouse or something like that?","start":354.265,"stop":359.154,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Clearly it would be included in the class.","start":359.154,"stop":361.045,"duration":1.89},{"text":"I can't point you to instances.","start":361.045,"stop":363.091,"duration":2.05},{"text":"I do know that there is at least one case which was decided in New York City which deals with a commercial rental property on which Manhattan Cable Television had made the installation, not Teleprompter.","start":363.091,"stop":375.007,"duration":11.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you're going to make that argument, then it applies to private residences.","start":375.007,"stop":381.02,"duration":6.01},{"text":"Literally, they're among the class, just as well as commercial property.","start":381.02,"stop":387.846,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"You've brought me to the exception which I was not going to go into, yes.","start":387.846,"stop":392.015,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":392.015,"stop":392.562,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"There is an exception for single family residences on which the installation serves the sole function of servicing that residence, the theory being obviously that the owner of that residence has in effect implicitly invited Teleprompter onto the property to render the service.","start":392.562,"stop":412.164,"duration":19.6},{"text":"But if the line continues from that television set on to the next property, it's a crossover and then that owner is within the class.","start":412.164,"stop":420.879,"duration":8.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose an owner who doesn't... an owner of a single family residence who doesn't want the service nevertheless has to put up with the wires in order for Teleprompter to get to the next property?","start":420.879,"stop":433.515,"duration":12.64},{"text":"Is that what you're suggesting?","start":433.515,"stop":437.091,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"If the premise is a non-rental premise, which I recognize can change from time to time, but if at the instance you're talking about it's non-rental, then the Court of Appeals has interpreted Section 828 as not covering that.","start":437.091,"stop":452.945,"duration":15.85},{"text":"So that the owner would be entitled to preclude entry by the television company.","start":452.945,"stop":459.082,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether he wants the service or not?","start":459.082,"stop":460.706,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course, it he wants it he's welcome to have it in and he can allow entry to the extent he wishes, precluding, if he wants, a crossover.","start":460.706,"stop":469.345,"duration":8.64},{"text":"We have urged here the observance of a per se or absolute rule in an era when we recognize that balancing of constitutional rights is popular, on the theory that it is traditional in the area of physical occupation of property or seizure of title to observe a per se rule, although this Court has seldom had an opportunity in perhaps the last century or so to apply that principle.","start":469.345,"stop":508.985,"duration":39.64},{"text":"There are some exceptions which I'll mention in a moment.","start":508.985,"stop":511.5,"duration":2.51},{"text":"Kaiser Aetna for one states that the right to exclude is universally held to be a fundamental element of the property right, which the government cannot take without compensation.","start":511.5,"stop":525.12,"duration":13.62},{"text":"And even if the government physically invades only an easement in property, it must nonetheless pay just compensation.","start":525.12,"stop":533.162,"duration":8.04},{"text":"In St. Louis versus Western Union, which is an 1893 case, this Court held that the installation of telegraph lines and poles in a municipality, no matter how de minimis that installation might be, constitutes a taking, and that the city's use of the top cross-arm of the pole constitutes a taking by the city.","start":533.162,"stop":562.182,"duration":29.02},{"text":"There's similar dictum of this Court in United States versus Causby, 1948, and one might also look to the Delaware Railroad case, 1928, where the Court held that a municipality's direction to a railroad company to set aside a portion of the private street running through the railroad station property as a taxi stand constitutes a taking.","start":562.182,"stop":593.42,"duration":31.24},{"text":"In none of these, I submit, was there any balancing approach with respect to the determination of whether a property right had been taken.","start":593.42,"stop":608.585,"duration":15.17},{"text":"The balancing approach does come in in regulation cases, such as PruneYard versus Robins, where the Court, on the basis of the ruling made in California, recognized that the people who had come onto the property to distribute literature and solicit signatures were part of the general public who were invited onto the property, were properly there, and were present by virtue of a special invitation made by the owner to the general public to come onto the property.","start":608.585,"stop":649.881,"duration":41.3},{"text":"And the question was, to what extent can the state regulate the activities of such people or the activities of the owner with respect to such people on the property.","start":649.881,"stop":663.813,"duration":13.93},{"text":"The regulation concept grew up entirely distinctly from the old-fashioned physical occupation or seizure of title concept.","start":663.813,"stop":676.948,"duration":13.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gruen, can this ordinance or statute be regarded as a form of regulation, to the extent that it affects the tenants, as opposed to the crossover, a landlord-tenant regulation?","start":676.948,"stop":692.972,"duration":16.02},{"text":"And there are many such regulations extant around the country requiring landlords to furnish utilities or other such requirements.","start":692.972,"stop":706.343,"duration":13.37}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, there certainly are and there are in New York as well.","start":706.343,"stop":711.482,"duration":5.14},{"text":"However, we've been unable to find any instance in which any such regulation, first of all, obliges the landlord to accept the installation of somebody else's property on his property.","start":711.482,"stop":725.209,"duration":13.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Permanently.","start":725.209,"stop":726.209,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Permanently... or for that matter, I can't think of any unpermanent one.","start":726.209,"stop":732.066,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How about telephone equipment?","start":732.066,"stop":739.563,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Telephone equipment is a--","start":739.563,"stop":744.171,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It continues to belong to the telephone company.","start":744.171,"stop":746.919,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's true, Your Honor.","start":746.919,"stop":748.263,"duration":1.34},{"text":"And to my knowledge there are no cases which oblige a landlord to permit the telephone company to enter property and make installations without compensation to the landlord.","start":748.263,"stop":761.772,"duration":13.51},{"text":"It is certainly very common that this happens, we recognize that, and we think it's because landlords recognize that telephone service is desirable, tenants want it.","start":761.772,"stop":772.145,"duration":10.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You found no statutory requirement that landlords allow tenants to be served by telephone service?","start":772.145,"stop":781.047,"duration":8.9}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":781.047,"stop":782.093,"duration":1.05},{"text":"As a matter of fact, in New York it's very clear that telephone companies are obliged by statute to provide compensation.","start":782.093,"stop":790.292,"duration":8.2},{"text":"And furthermore, there is written into the law a protection for the practical situation where the landlord does permit the telephone company to come in, as in through an informal license, without requiring compensation.","start":790.292,"stop":806.082,"duration":15.79},{"text":"That statute says that no prescriptive easement or right can arise as a result of this informal permission.","start":806.082,"stop":813.581,"duration":7.5},{"text":"So you have a very different situation from Section 828, which obliges the landlord to accept the presence of this stranger's property, and indeed creates a very strong possibility that 20 years later the telephone company... the cable company will have earned a prescriptive easement.","start":813.581,"stop":838.711,"duration":25.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you mean you think that Section 828 would be defensible if it contained an additional provision that said no prescriptive right will attach?","start":838.711,"stop":850.253,"duration":11.54}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":850.253,"stop":852.048,"duration":1.79},{"text":"I think that a situation would be defensible... that such a provision might be desirable, but it would only protect as to a voluntary acceptance by the landlord of the presence of the cable facilities on his property.","start":852.048,"stop":875.212,"duration":23.16},{"text":"I think that what creates the problem here is that the government insists that the landlord allow the cable company to make its installation.","start":875.212,"stop":884.941,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would you think it would be different if the law said... if the law said: in one paragraph, all apartment buildings will be equipped with sprinkler systems for fire prevention; section two, all apartment buildings shall be equipped with cables or equipment so that television... or so that tenants may easily plug into cable television.","start":884.941,"stop":915.148,"duration":30.21},{"text":"A regulation that required the landlord to make these installations, like he does sprinklers or hot water heaters or something else?","start":915.148,"stop":925.004,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that solves half the problem, Your Honor.","start":925.004,"stop":926.77,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Half the problem?","start":926.77,"stop":927.518,"duration":0.75},{"text":"Does it solve it all or not?","start":927.518,"stop":928.987,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it would not solve it all, because the second part of--","start":928.987,"stop":932.204,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it wouldn't be a taking problem then, would it?","start":932.204,"stop":935.14,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--I believe it would, Your Honor, insofar as it requires a substantial expenditure without compensation.","start":935.14,"stop":943.137,"duration":8},{"text":"We don't have this case, but I think that what--","start":943.137,"stop":947.214,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what about, say, installing a sprinkler system?","start":947.214,"stop":950.26,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Very expensive.","start":950.26,"stop":951.244,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, that's true, and at least in New York a landlord is entitled to compensation in the form of rent, increased rent, for making such improvements on his property.","start":951.244,"stop":963.222,"duration":11.98},{"text":"I think this is the second factor which distinguishes our case from the safety and health measure cases, such as sprinkler systems and the like.","start":963.222,"stop":971.72,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you say that that comes under the police power as a matter of public safety, because it involves not only the safety of one tenant, but--","start":971.72,"stop":980.091,"duration":8.37}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think it does, Your Honor.","start":980.091,"stop":982.388,"duration":2.3},{"text":"I think where the problem is presented in New York with respect to such rules is because of the existence of the pervasive system of rent control.","start":982.388,"stop":991.133,"duration":8.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--But you would say that the benefits of television are not as great as the benefit of being free from a fire, is that it?","start":991.133,"stop":997.678,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I would certainly say that, yes.","start":997.678,"stop":1002.925,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would it solve your problem if the law said in section two, it said, you will install these Teleprompter or these cable television cables whenever some cable television company will pay you for it?","start":1002.925,"stop":1018.123,"duration":15.2},{"text":"That wouldn't, cost you anything.","start":1018.123,"stop":1023.574,"duration":5.45},{"text":"Any time they offer to pay for the installation, you'll put them all over.","start":1023.574,"stop":1029.306,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, of course, such a payment would have to be made in advance, and I assume that's part of your question.","start":1029.306,"stop":1035.506,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1035.506,"stop":1035.724,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't solve the entire problem, interestingly enough.","start":1035.724,"stop":1040.581,"duration":4.86},{"text":"It changes the precise location of the easement from the surface of the roof to inside the wire.","start":1040.581,"stop":1047.548,"duration":6.97},{"text":"Here you're positing that the wire itself is owned of the landlord, but the cable company has the right to pass its signal through the wire without compensation to the landlord, for its commercial benefit.","start":1047.548,"stop":1061.214,"duration":13.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the tenant.","start":1061.214,"stop":1061.433,"duration":0.22},{"text":"The tenant has the right to pass it through from where it's connected on the outside of the building.","start":1061.433,"stop":1066.322,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"You're asking, supposing the tenant could make an installation from the outside of the building to his particular apartment?","start":1066.322,"stop":1073.663,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1073.663,"stop":1073.991,"duration":0.33},{"text":"The landlord has from the edge of his building to all the tenants' apartments, he has installed a cable, for which he's been paid.","start":1073.991,"stop":1082.502,"duration":8.51},{"text":"And the cable company comes along and just plugs in at the edge of his property.","start":1082.502,"stop":1088.203,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I think if obliged by the government, that that would have to be compensated in some form.","start":1088.203,"stop":1102.026,"duration":13.82},{"text":"And I think that this--","start":1102.026,"stop":1104.182,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they've paid him for the expense.","start":1104.182,"stop":1105.539,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry?","start":1105.539,"stop":1106.102,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The cable company pays him the expense.","start":1106.102,"stop":1108.446,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1108.446,"stop":1108.789,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He's not out of pocket.","start":1108.789,"stop":1109.508,"duration":0.72},{"text":"But you say there's still an appropriation of his property?","start":1109.508,"stop":1112.459,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I would not have a problem with your example in a state other than New York, which doesn't have rent control.","start":1112.459,"stop":1118.254,"duration":5.79},{"text":"There I would assume that the landlord can set whatever rents he wishes and thereby compensate himself for the expenditures he makes in improving the property.","start":1118.254,"stop":1128.25,"duration":10},{"text":"New York presents the problem that there is no way of a landlord compensating himself for such an expenditure other than by a permitted increase in rent, and in fact I think that's why New York allows for increases in rent for virtually all of the examples which this Court has proposed in the oral discussion now.","start":1128.25,"stop":1152.475,"duration":24.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you suggest, Mr. Gruen, that... are there New York statutes which require landlords, say in apartment buildings, to install sprinkler systems, smoke detectors and that sort of thing?","start":1152.475,"stop":1162.891,"duration":10.42}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there are.","start":1162.891,"stop":1163.298,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And what do they say as to compensation?","start":1163.298,"stop":1166.5,"duration":3.2},{"text":"I didn't catch that?","start":1166.5,"stop":1167.141,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"There was one very recently adopted with respect to smoke detectors.","start":1167.141,"stop":1170.81,"duration":3.67},{"text":"It requires that the tenant pay the landlord for a particular price which is the presumptive price of the smoke detector.","start":1170.81,"stop":1179.214,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":1179.214,"stop":1179.885,"duration":0.67},{"text":"So actually the cost is paid by the tenant, not by the landlord?","start":1179.885,"stop":1183.493,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1183.493,"stop":1183.743,"duration":0.25},{"text":"And furthermore, that the tenant maintains the smoke detector.","start":1183.743,"stop":1186.242,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's not paid by the landlord here, either.","start":1186.242,"stop":1187.273,"duration":1.03},{"text":"The cost of installation isn't paid by the landlord.","start":1187.273,"stop":1190.131,"duration":2.86},{"text":"It's going to be paid by the cable company.","start":1190.131,"stop":1192.739,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1192.739,"stop":1193.146,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So he doesn't have to charge the tenant for the cost.","start":1193.146,"stop":1195.863,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1195.863,"stop":1197.956,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But he's not paid by the tenant for the fact that the sprinklers occupy a piece of his property.","start":1197.956,"stop":1203.015,"duration":5.06},{"text":"Well, the sprinklers becomes his property, I suppose, become the landlord's property.","start":1203.015,"stop":1210.482,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, of course, and he's indemnified by whatever he wishes to charge in rent for the cost of the sprinklers.","start":1210.482,"stop":1215.683,"duration":5.2},{"text":"There's a slight difference between a smoke alarm and the cable installation, because the smoke alarm is within the tenant's own apartment, it occupies no additional space not let by the original demise.","start":1215.683,"stop":1229.88,"duration":14.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gruen, aren't you... you're arguing mainly a question of compensation.","start":1229.88,"stop":1233.051,"duration":3.17},{"text":"I thought your basic position in the brief was that there's a basic distinction between a physical invasion by a third party and a regulation which requires the owner of the property to do something to his own property, and then you have a question of whether that amounts to a taking.","start":1233.051,"stop":1246.108,"duration":13.06},{"text":"And aren't all these examples that have been given to you simply forms of regulation?","start":1246.108,"stop":1249.435,"duration":3.33},{"text":"They don't even approach the basic argument that you've made, isn't that right?","start":1249.435,"stop":1253.745,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they are.","start":1253.745,"stop":1254.948,"duration":1.2},{"text":"I think they grow out of a hypothetical--","start":1254.948,"stop":1259.79,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They are reasonable regulations of an owner's use of his property.","start":1259.79,"stop":1263.445,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, yes, and particularly because they involve some measure of compensation, I think that they--","start":1263.445,"stop":1270.38,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's arguable they might not even require compensation if you look at them as... if you view them as regulatory rather than as takings, rather than as physical invasions.","start":1270.38,"stop":1278.361,"duration":7.98}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--They certainly involve a different level--","start":1278.361,"stop":1283.687,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"None of them involves a physical invasion, which I understand to be your principal argument.","start":1283.687,"stop":1287.216,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's absolutely correct.","start":1287.216,"stop":1288.872,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the phone company's invasion in New York apartments, where they run the wire right straight up the wall?","start":1288.872,"stop":1295.525,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as a landlord I have a perfect right to tell the phone company that I don't want them on my property.","start":1295.525,"stop":1300.71,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don't do it.","start":1300.71,"stop":1301.492,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I may choose not to, and in fact most landlords--","start":1301.492,"stop":1305.225,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't do it.","start":1305.225,"stop":1305.444,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry?","start":1305.444,"stop":1306.163,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't do it, and the tenant has his space taken and the landlord's space, too.","start":1306.163,"stop":1312.488,"duration":6.33},{"text":"The phone company uses both spaces to run its cables through in New York.","start":1312.488,"stop":1318.673,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":1318.673,"stop":1319.564,"duration":0.89},{"text":"But it's the landlord's voluntary choice not to charge the cable company... the telephone company.","start":1319.564,"stop":1326.044,"duration":6.48},{"text":"He has a perfect right to charge the telephone company if he chooses to.","start":1326.044,"stop":1329.09,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the landlord could build an apartment building and simply say that he thinks telephones are an abomination and there'll be no telephones in this building and no telephone wires in the building, could he not?","start":1329.09,"stop":1338.992,"duration":9.9}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"He could.","start":1338.992,"stop":1339.648,"duration":0.66},{"text":"He may get relatively few tenants--","start":1339.648,"stop":1341.788,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He might have trouble getting tenants.","start":1341.788,"stop":1343.132,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--It's his choice with his property.","start":1343.132,"stop":1344.63,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"On the other hand, he might get a lot of tenants that way.","start":1344.63,"stop":1347.067,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry?","start":1347.067,"stop":1348.082,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He might get a lot of tenants.","start":1348.082,"stop":1349.41,"duration":1.33},{"text":"There might be some peculiar people.","start":1349.41,"stop":1350.768,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I might choose to live there.","start":1350.768,"stop":1351.471,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Just think of the speech interest.","start":1351.471,"stop":1353.533,"duration":2.06},{"text":"Mr. Gruen, does the presence of the cable equipment increase the rental value of the apartment?","start":1353.533,"stop":1365.621,"duration":12.09}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually, it doesn't.","start":1365.621,"stop":1370.229,"duration":4.61},{"text":"If one thinks this through in the New York context, it's quite clear that it can't.","start":1370.229,"stop":1376.868,"duration":6.64},{"text":"There is a virtually nonexistent vacancy rate in New York and therefore the presence of cable is unlikely to add additional tenancy to the building.","start":1376.868,"stop":1388.786,"duration":11.92},{"text":"And Section 828 absolutely prohibits the landlord from asking increased rent because of the presence of the cable.","start":1388.786,"stop":1396.922,"duration":8.14},{"text":"Therefore, you have no income to capitalize into a higher value.","start":1396.922,"stop":1401.155,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm no fan of most television, but how many channels are available in New York City area on cable?","start":1401.155,"stop":1409.495,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm afraid I can't answer that, Your Honor.","start":1409.495,"stop":1412.338,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There are a lot of them.","start":1412.338,"stop":1412.93,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I think quite a few.","start":1412.93,"stop":1414.649,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you one other factual question.","start":1414.649,"stop":1419.632,"duration":4.98},{"text":"You started out by pointing out that before the ordinance was passed your opponent used a form which gave the landlord five percent of whatever revenues were derived from that building.","start":1419.632,"stop":1429.191,"duration":9.56}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1429.191,"stop":1429.785,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"As to... and they're five-year term license agreements, as I understand it.","start":1429.785,"stop":1433.829,"duration":4.04},{"text":"As to those which were in effect and had three or four years to run when the ordinance was passed, did they continue to have payment being made to the landlord or is that money now paid to the city pursuant to the ordinance?","start":1433.829,"stop":1446.731,"duration":12.9}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the payments to the city are a completely separate item.","start":1446.731,"stop":1452.133,"duration":5.4},{"text":"The payments to the landlords, according to one statement in the record of Teleprompter in an appendix to an agreement with Hughes Aircraft, said that the payments to the landlords continued to be made until mid-1974 under contracts, and at that point, apparently whether the contract had time to run or not, Teleprompter simply ceased making the payments.","start":1452.133,"stop":1474.486,"duration":22.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"As I read the ordinance, it would prohibit the continued payment pursuant to those agreements.","start":1474.486,"stop":1478.639,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I agree with you.","start":1478.639,"stop":1481.435,"duration":2.8},{"text":"You understand that the payments to the city are entirely distinct.","start":1481.435,"stop":1489.29,"duration":7.86},{"text":"They're made under the franchise agreement, so-called, with the city and they consist of five percent of gross revenues.","start":1489.29,"stop":1496.303,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But aren't they the same five percent of gross revenues?","start":1496.303,"stop":1498.584,"duration":2.28},{"text":"I mean, say--","start":1498.584,"stop":1499.021,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"They're a different five percent.","start":1499.021,"stop":1500.349,"duration":1.33},{"text":"It adds up to ten.","start":1500.349,"stop":1501.379,"duration":1.03},{"text":"That five percent to the city is paid for a precisely analogous use to that which is made of the rooftops on our blocks.","start":1501.379,"stop":1512.751,"duration":11.37},{"text":"It's for the use of the city streets for the passage of cable underneath.","start":1512.751,"stop":1518.592,"duration":5.84},{"text":"And I should make clear that the right of landlords to be free of such installations in New York or to be compensated for them if they chose to be was extremely clear under case law in New York up until 1973.","start":1518.592,"stop":1545.112,"duration":26.52},{"text":"There are innumerable cases which stay that any installation made by a tenant outside of his own apartment can be prohibited by the landlord, and if the landlord chooses to allow it to persist the landlord is entitled to compensation for it.","start":1545.112,"stop":1564.042,"duration":18.93},{"text":"In particular, there are a number of cases dealing with television antenna installations on rooftops, where the courts say that the landlord may prohibit it or receive compensation, and rent control regulations up until 1973 provided for compensation.","start":1564.042,"stop":1582.643,"duration":18.6},{"text":"I would propose to reserve the balance of my time.","start":1582.643,"stop":1586.704,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--May I just ask you--","start":1586.704,"stop":1587.361,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, please.","start":1587.361,"stop":1588.079,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--would the rationale of the court below sustain an ordinance which told all landlords that, you must maintain in the basement a room in which vending machine companies may place their vending machines, or laundromat operators may place their laundromat, for the convenience of tenants?","start":1588.079,"stop":1607.946,"duration":19.87}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"I see no substantive difference between Section 828 and such a regulation.","start":1607.946,"stop":1613.568,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The rationale would seem to reach it.","start":1613.568,"stop":1616.63,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1616.63,"stop":1617.098,"duration":0.47},{"text":"I think the rationale is that essentially the Constitution as viewed by the Court of Appeals in New York--","start":1617.098,"stop":1626.22,"duration":9.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Or you must make a space on your roof for a swimming pool company to put in a swimming pool?","start":1626.22,"stop":1630.781,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"--I agree.","start":1630.781,"stop":1631.265,"duration":0.48},{"text":"I think it says that landlords may be required to permit any use of their property which doesn't in effect... which is beneficial to the tenants and which doesn't in effect utterly destroy the value of the property.","start":1631.265,"stop":1644.479,"duration":13.21},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1644.479,"stop":1646.571,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Griswold, at your own time somewhere will you address the question of whether a person could lawfully build an apartment and do as I suggested, simply say, I don't want any telephones in my apartment building, I don't want any television sets that require an outside antenna?","start":1646.571,"stop":1676.543,"duration":29.97}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That, Mr. Chief Justice, is a question of New York law.","start":1676.543,"stop":1684.196,"duration":7.65},{"text":"On it I would rely on the opinion filed in this case by the Attorney General of New York, in which he says that if a tenant wants telephone service that he can apply to the Public Service Commission of New York, which would direct the telephone company to condemn an easement to provide the television service to that building.","start":1684.196,"stop":1709.921,"duration":25.73},{"text":"I think that as I understand the law of New York, the landlord could not prevent the installation of telephone service.","start":1709.921,"stop":1717.714,"duration":7.79},{"text":"But under the statutory law of New York, which goes back 90 years, that right to enter the premises would be obtained by condemning an easement.","start":1717.714,"stop":1729.866,"duration":12.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He'd be compensated for it?","start":1729.866,"stop":1731.395,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"A compensated one.","start":1731.395,"stop":1732.911,"duration":1.52},{"text":"I--","start":1732.911,"stop":1733.74,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is not the case here.","start":1733.74,"stop":1735.893,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--I like to suggest that this is really a kind of an academic question, quite apart from that lovely apartment building that the Chief Justice would like to live in.","start":1735.893,"stop":1745.687,"duration":9.79},{"text":"But I think the fact that there simply aren't any cases on this arises from the fact that no landlord would dream of telling a tenant that you can't have a telephone in your place.","start":1745.687,"stop":1759.04,"duration":13.35},{"text":"It's simply taken for granted.","start":1759.04,"stop":1764.023,"duration":4.98},{"text":"I think it's important to look at the terms of this statute, which appears in the appendix to our red brief.","start":1764.023,"stop":1778.563,"duration":14.54},{"text":"Section 828: \"No landlord\"--","start":1778.563,"stop":1784.545,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What page is that?","start":1784.545,"stop":1785.342,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--It's page 2a in the appendix of the brief.","start":1785.342,"stop":1789.622,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1789.622,"stop":1789.888,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"\"No landlord shall\":","start":1789.888,"stop":1791.949,"duration":2.06},{"text":"\"(a) Interfere with the installation of cable television facilities upon his property or premises, except that a landlord may require. \"","start":1791.949,"stop":1802.319,"duration":10.37},{"text":"\"(1) that the installation of cable television facilities conform to such reasonable conditions as are necessary to protect the safety, functioning, and appearance of the premises, and the convenience and well being of other tenants. \"","start":1802.319,"stop":1822.562,"duration":20.24},{"text":"\"(2) that the cable television company or the tenant or a combination thereof bear the entire cost of the installation, operation or removal of such facilities. \"","start":1822.562,"stop":1835.931,"duration":13.37},{"text":"\"and (3), that the cable television company agree to indemnify the landlord for any damage caused by the installation, operation or removal of such facilities. \"","start":1835.931,"stop":1849.848,"duration":13.92},{"text":"And then (b):","start":1849.848,"stop":1851.723,"duration":1.88},{"text":"\"Demand or accept payment from any tenant in any form in exchange for permitting cable television service on or within his property or premises, or from any cable television in exchange therefore in excess of any amount which the Commission shall by regulation determine to be reasonable. \"","start":1851.723,"stop":1876.196,"duration":24.47},{"text":"Now, I won't read the rest, though it is relevant.","start":1876.196,"stop":1880.507,"duration":4.31},{"text":"There are other provisions of the statute which set up a cable television commission which has authority to make awards.","start":1880.507,"stop":1890.754,"duration":10.25},{"text":"It has made a general regulation to the effect that there is no damage, that there is no loss to a landlord in the ordinary case, and that the ordinary landlord is entitled to simply a nominal payment, which is one time, one dollar.","start":1890.754,"stop":1907.98,"duration":17.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But that just assumes the answer to the question, that it's perfectly all right to take a piece of your property as long as it doesn't lover its value.","start":1907.98,"stop":1916.946,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it doesn't assume question.","start":1916.946,"stop":1920.32,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it suggests an answer to the question.","start":1920.32,"stop":1922.193,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"It suggests an answer, made by the state.","start":1922.193,"stop":1924.506,"duration":2.31},{"text":"And that I think gets to the heart of the case, because here the Appellant's case depends upon the assertion that Mrs. Loretto's property has been taken.","start":1924.506,"stop":1938.203,"duration":13.7},{"text":"But that begs the question.","start":1938.203,"stop":1940.593,"duration":2.39},{"text":"The issue here is what is the extent of the landlord's property after a lease has been made.","start":1940.593,"stop":1949.886,"duration":9.29},{"text":"This is property which, when Mrs. Loretto owns it alone and keeps it vacant, is undoubtedly hers, and Section 828 has no application to it.","start":1949.886,"stop":1962.068,"duration":12.18},{"text":"But when she chooses to devote the property to rental purposes, that connotes a divided ownership of the property.","start":1962.068,"stop":1972.017,"duration":9.95},{"text":"She no longer is the sole owner of that property, and the tenant has rights not only with respect to, shall I say, the six walls of the apartment, but also has a great many other rights with respect to the usage of that building.","start":1972.017,"stop":1989.855,"duration":17.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Then if you treat this as a right, then does the statute not take something away from the tenants without compensation?","start":1989.855,"stop":1997.398,"duration":7.54}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it gives it to the tenant.","start":1997.398,"stop":2000.74,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It depends on whether you regard this as a boon or otherwise, I suppose.","start":2000.74,"stop":2005.504,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"It does not in any way interfere with the tenant's use of any rights which he may have in the overall premises.","start":2005.504,"stop":2015.703,"duration":10.2},{"text":"It does facilitate his use, if he chooses, to have cable television.","start":2015.703,"stop":2021.733,"duration":6.03},{"text":"But let's suppose, for example, that a landlord makes a lease and when the tenant arrives with the moving van the landlord stands at the door and says: Stop, there's nothing in the lease about bringing in furniture.","start":2021.733,"stop":2036.788,"duration":15.06},{"text":"Or suppose the landlord says, there's nothing in the lease about bringing in food; that will attract mice and that will lead to vermin, and I must insist as a health measure that you not bring in food.","start":2036.788,"stop":2051.548,"duration":14.76},{"text":"Of course the landlord would not be sustained, even though there was no provision in the lease about this.","start":2051.548,"stop":2058.264,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what if the lease said that you can't bring in furniture or food?","start":2058.264,"stop":2062.122,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that would be entirely different.","start":2062.122,"stop":2065.354,"duration":3.23},{"text":"And the lease in this case couldn't do that because the New York legislature has--","start":2065.354,"stop":2069.805,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, supposing there was a lease before this statute was passed in which the landlord said, you may not have cable television in our premises, because we think it's a nuisance?","start":2069.805,"stop":2077.177,"duration":7.37},{"text":"That was a term of the lease.","start":2077.177,"stop":2080.817,"duration":3.64},{"text":"The landlord said that--","start":2080.817,"stop":2081.378,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--And New York has changed the law with respect to the respective rights of landlord and tenant, and our position would be that that is a standard part of the powers of a state legislature, to regulate the rights of landlord and tenant.","start":2081.378,"stop":2101.481,"duration":20.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--But that doesn't cover the crossovers, does it?","start":2101.481,"stop":2105.166,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case the landlord is subjected to no costs.","start":2105.166,"stop":2109.445,"duration":4.28},{"text":"The costs are entirely paid by the television company or by the tenant.","start":2109.445,"stop":2115.131,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But in effect this landlord is required not only to provide for the tenants of her property, but to provide for the tenants of some other landlord by giving a crossover.","start":2115.131,"stop":2124.347,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that gets to... that gets to the question of crossovers, which of course is very important.","start":2124.347,"stop":2133.077,"duration":8.73},{"text":"I would like to suggest, before I get to crossovers, which is an essential issue in the case here, suppose this was a single family house to begin with, on a plot of land, and it was leased.","start":2133.077,"stop":2148.633,"duration":15.56},{"text":"A tenant obtained it and the tenant, having a three-year lease, says, I want cable television.","start":2148.633,"stop":2158.378,"duration":9.75},{"text":"It seems to me extremely unlikely that any court would hold that the tenant, having the rights which a tenant of a three-year lease of a single family house, did not have enough property rights to entitle him to bring in cable television.","start":2158.378,"stop":2177.715,"duration":19.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know.","start":2177.715,"stop":2178.637,"duration":0.92},{"text":"I think it's a pretty normal provision in leases not to permit fixtures without the consent of the landlord.","start":2178.637,"stop":2187.117,"duration":8.48},{"text":"It's a perfectly straightforward provision in every lease.","start":2187.117,"stop":2191.364,"duration":4.25}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That depends on how you define \"fixtures\".","start":2191.364,"stop":2194.317,"duration":2.95},{"text":"I suppose that building an addition--","start":2194.317,"stop":2195.895,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I would hesitate to think this wasn't a fixture.","start":2195.895,"stop":2198.628,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--It's certainly removable.","start":2198.628,"stop":2202.268,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It may be, but--","start":2202.268,"stop":2204.11,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Fixtures usually are not removable.","start":2204.11,"stop":2205.874,"duration":1.76},{"text":"That's part of the definition.","start":2205.874,"stop":2207.656,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the way these are described, they're pretty well plugged into the building.","start":2207.656,"stop":2210.374,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Well, we ought to be careful, taking about New York City apartment leases.","start":2210.374,"stop":2215.715,"duration":5.34},{"text":"Because of the 30 or 40 provisions in the lease, the tenant only has one protection, one provision to protect the tenant.","start":2215.715,"stop":2227.241,"duration":11.53},{"text":"That gives him the right to pay.","start":2227.241,"stop":2229.458,"duration":2.22},{"text":"And all the others... for example, one provision is if the landlord decides that the tenant is not a decent person he can throw him out.","start":2229.458,"stop":2239.002,"duration":9.54},{"text":"And another provision, I hereby give up my right to a jury trial.","start":2239.002,"stop":2244.375,"duration":5.37},{"text":"I don't think those are common all over, but they are legal in New York and are approved by the New York courts.","start":2244.375,"stop":2254.778,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think in due course I will come to a few rights that the tenant does have.","start":2254.778,"stop":2262.664,"duration":7.89},{"text":"I would like to point out that this particular statute is 24 supportable in our view not merely by the power of New York to regulate the respective interests of landlord and tenant in rental property, but also by the clearly supported, in the legislative history and in the findings of the statute, interest of the State of New York in fostering and developing improved communications and educational facilities.","start":2262.664,"stop":2293.262,"duration":30.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I interrupt you on that argument?","start":2293.262,"stop":2294.465,"duration":1.2},{"text":"Supposing the statute changed the words \"cable television\" to the word \"telephone\".","start":2294.465,"stop":2299.9,"duration":5.43},{"text":"Everywhere it says \"cable\" it said \"telephone\", and otherwise it were precisely the same, there's an interest in communication by telephone.","start":2299.9,"stop":2305.539,"duration":5.64},{"text":"Would that be lawful, constitutional?","start":2305.539,"stop":2307.429,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would be, Mr. Justice, and I would suggest that for all practical purposes that is the law of New York today.","start":2307.429,"stop":2315.159,"duration":7.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought earlier we had agreed that if there were to be a television installation it would be a taking for which there'd have to be condemnation and a payment?","start":2315.159,"stop":2324.141,"duration":8.98}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the statutory law of New York, which went back to very early days and much more conventional notions of taking than have been developed in this Court, let's say in the last ten years... PruneYard and a good many labor cases--","start":2324.141,"stop":2344.726,"duration":20.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"New York Central.","start":2344.726,"stop":2345.633,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, certainly.","start":2345.633,"stop":2348.304,"duration":2.67},{"text":"I think it's Penn Central.","start":2348.304,"stop":2349.927,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Penn Central.","start":2349.927,"stop":2350.349,"duration":0.42},{"text":"Excuse me.","start":2350.349,"stop":2350.896,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That's one of the cases to which we will refer.","start":2350.896,"stop":2355.533,"duration":4.64},{"text":"I wouldn't doubt myself that if New York were now to repeal that telephone statute, which requires... is interpreted to require the taking and paying, and to substitute a statute like 828, I'd rather like to argue that case here.","start":2355.533,"stop":2374.699,"duration":19.17},{"text":"I kind of think maybe it could be won.","start":2374.699,"stop":2377.588,"duration":2.89},{"text":"At least that's the--","start":2377.588,"stop":2378.275,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It'd really be quite a departure from what the telephone companies in 50 states have been doing for a long, long time, wouldn't it?","start":2378.275,"stop":2383.961,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think so, Mr. Justice.","start":2383.961,"stop":2385.568,"duration":1.61},{"text":"I think you will find... you will find that it is very hard to find that any telephone company has paid for that right for a long, long time.","start":2385.568,"stop":2394.8,"duration":9.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say paid for that right, Mr. Griswold, do you mean the right to have an easement to string poles?","start":2394.8,"stop":2399.921,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't mean it.","start":2399.921,"stop":2401.734,"duration":1.81},{"text":"I mean the right to bring in a feeder line to lead telephone service into a residence or into a business building.","start":2401.734,"stop":2409.496,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what if New York amended 828 to provide that, because of our interest in communications, in the event that there isn't any telephone... system of telephone poles in this particular area... let's assume the poles are above ground... that any landlord shall allow the telephone company to put a pole in his back yard, without having to pay for it?","start":2409.496,"stop":2431.567,"duration":22.07}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that there is a distinction between what I call trunk lines and feeder lines, and there are old cases of this Court, 100 years ago, involving telephone... telegraph companies putting their lines down city streets and down railroad rights of way, and it was held that they had to pay for that right.","start":2431.567,"stop":2455.119,"duration":23.55},{"text":"And I would suspect that if New York passed a statute saying that any cable television company is entitled to put its trunk lines on private property without paying, that that would not be held to be constitutional.","start":2455.119,"stop":2474.049,"duration":18.93},{"text":"I think it is different with respect to feeder lines, and that perhaps is an appropriate place for me to come to the crossover problem.","start":2474.049,"stop":2489.761,"duration":15.71},{"text":"There are two kinds of crossovers, as I see it.","start":2489.761,"stop":2495.602,"duration":5.84},{"text":"The New York Court of Appeals said there were three, but I think that two of those present the same legal issue.","start":2495.602,"stop":2503.537,"duration":7.93},{"text":"One is what I call the short crossover, and that is that when the cable comes in on the roof to this building, having come from the adjacent building on this side and serving a tenant in this building, then the cable continues, and the record shows in this case four to six feet, in order to bring service to the next building.","start":2503.537,"stop":2531.322,"duration":27.79},{"text":"And we suggest, first, that that's de minimis; and second, that there is a clear quid pro quo in it, because this building's tenants get the service because there's a crossover from the next building, and to say that in order to do that you have to provide the same kind of a lead to the adjoining building on the other side doesn't seem very serious.","start":2531.322,"stop":2562.777,"duration":31.45},{"text":"But in any event, we would contend that that is not a taking requiring a payment under the Fifth Amendment as applied to the states by the Fourteenth.","start":2562.777,"stop":2580.74,"duration":17.96},{"text":"Now, the other one is what I call the pure crossover, and that is the situation where there is no tenant in this building who has cable television, but the cable television company wants to bring the cable from the building on the right across this building in order to get to the building on the left.","start":2580.74,"stop":2607.041,"duration":26.3},{"text":"And I would say that even that, even as applied to that, the statute is valid, just as the New York statute now provides that a person who builds a new apartment house must provide it with water and sewer service.","start":2607.041,"stop":2627.158,"duration":20.12},{"text":"There are no tenants in the building when he is building it.","start":2627.158,"stop":2629.268,"duration":2.11},{"text":"There may be no tenants for six months after he has completed it if his rents are so high that he can't get people in.","start":2629.268,"stop":2636.718,"duration":7.45},{"text":"Nevertheless, he won't get a building permit to start with unless he provides water and sewer service.","start":2636.718,"stop":2644.776,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You necessarily say that if you added to the water and sewer telephone lines, that they must provide telephone lines too if this statute includes it?","start":2644.776,"stop":2658.13,"duration":13.35}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, Mr. Justice, Mr. Chief Justice, that if New York should change its statute and say that a person building a new multiple dwelling apartment house must provide telephone lines in the building when it's built, that such a statute would be clearly constitutional.","start":2658.13,"stop":2677.451,"duration":19.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And laundromats and a room for vending machines?","start":2677.451,"stop":2681.574,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Laundromats and room for vending machines become more difficult, but--","start":2681.574,"stop":2686.243,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know why.","start":2686.243,"stop":2688.822,"duration":2.58},{"text":"I don't know why, under the rationale of the court below, a requirement that a landlord set aside this space and let vending machine people come in wouldn't be sustainable.","start":2688.822,"stop":2702.425,"duration":13.6}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, perhaps this is the time for me to come to another part of my argument.","start":2702.425,"stop":2710.515,"duration":8.09},{"text":"The contention is made by Mrs. Loretto's counsel that several of the cases that I would bring before you, including a whole series of labor cases which have completely denied the right of the owner of property to exclude people... the owner of property under this Court's decision has to admit union representatives under certain circumstances--","start":2710.515,"stop":2741.722,"duration":31.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Were those cases statute or constitutional arguments?","start":2741.722,"stop":2745.876,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--Those are affirming orders of the National Labor Relations Board.","start":2745.876,"stop":2750.531,"duration":4.65},{"text":"They have the general statute--","start":2750.531,"stop":2752.671,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's Babcock.","start":2752.671,"stop":2753.436,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--Babcock, that's right.","start":2753.436,"stop":2755.247,"duration":1.81},{"text":"--of fair dealing behind it, but no specific--","start":2755.247,"stop":2757.606,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But rejecting constitutional objections.","start":2757.606,"stop":2761.151,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--They do reject the constitutional objection, and do it... and do it on a--","start":2761.151,"stop":2770.694,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"PruneYard basis.","start":2770.694,"stop":2772.083,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, PruneYard is another one of them.","start":2772.083,"stop":2775.723,"duration":3.64},{"text":"But the Republic Aviation case, one of the early ones, quotes Judge Augustus Hand, who was dealing with a ship and union organizers wanted to go on board the ship, which was really the only place that they could get to the employees, because otherwise the ship's on the high seas.","start":2775.723,"stop":2800.714,"duration":24.99},{"text":"And Justice Augustus Hand said, it is not every interference with property rights which is within the Fifth Amendment.","start":2800.714,"stop":2809.647,"duration":8.93},{"text":"And this Court has followed that in the labor cases.","start":2809.647,"stop":2813.973,"duration":4.33},{"text":"We think that the PruneYard case is another clear example of that.","start":2813.973,"stop":2822.188,"duration":8.22},{"text":"California said, through its Supreme Court, applying its constitution, that the owner of a shopping center was required to allow the admission of people for the purpose of soliciting signatures and distributing literature.","start":2822.188,"stop":2844.163,"duration":21.97},{"text":"And this Court held that that was not a taking requiring compensation under the Fifth Amendment.","start":2844.163,"stop":2854.098,"duration":9.93},{"text":"But--","start":2854.098,"stop":2854.409,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a qualitative difference, however, between a temporary use of property and a permanent occupation of a portion of the space?","start":2854.409,"stop":2864.672,"duration":10.26}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Justice O'Connor, that's just the point I am coming to.","start":2864.672,"stop":2870.717,"duration":6.05},{"text":"Our friends say that this is a permanent occupation.","start":2870.717,"stop":2875.87,"duration":5.15},{"text":"I would suggest in the first place that it is not a permanent occupation.","start":2875.87,"stop":2880.072,"duration":4.2},{"text":"It's an occupation only as long as the landlord chooses to use this for rental purposes.","start":2880.072,"stop":2885.131,"duration":5.06},{"text":"The landlord can occupy the building himself and Section 828 no longer has any application.","start":2885.131,"stop":2893.378,"duration":8.25},{"text":"In other words, it is what we call a use-dependent regulation.","start":2893.378,"stop":2899.141,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose that's a little like the argument that the employer in the labor cases could go out of business if he wanted to.","start":2899.141,"stop":2903.672,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That the employer--","start":2903.672,"stop":2905.811,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In the labor cases, could just go out of business, and then he wouldn't be subjected to this invasion of his property any more.","start":2905.811,"stop":2910.637,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, no.","start":2910.637,"stop":2911.403,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's what you're saying here.","start":2911.403,"stop":2913.62,"duration":2.22},{"text":"The landlords could always go out of the rental business.","start":2913.62,"stop":2915.651,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Go out of the rental business, yes, but not necessarily go out of business.","start":2915.651,"stop":2919.368,"duration":3.72},{"text":"I have put together a list of 17 instances where there are permanent occupations of a landlord's premises.","start":2919.368,"stop":2932.05,"duration":12.68},{"text":"Sprinklers has already been referred to, and this Court in the Queenside Hills Realty Company case upheld the validity of that statutory provisions.","start":2932.05,"stop":2944.42,"duration":12.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know that sprinklers is right on point, though, because the landlord owns the sprinkler.","start":2944.42,"stop":2950.371,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That suggestion is also made by our opponents.","start":2950.371,"stop":2955.713,"duration":5.34},{"text":"Would this statute be better if it said that the landlord must put in cable television and he owns it and he pays for it?","start":2955.713,"stop":2964.194,"duration":8.48},{"text":"It seems to me that here the landlord is better off, less burdened by a statute which says--","start":2964.194,"stop":2971.488,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But the sprinkler is a matter of public safety, not only for the landlord but for all his tenants.","start":2971.488,"stop":2977.454,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, that's also--","start":2977.454,"stop":2979.796,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the safety factor, the police power factor, in television?","start":2979.796,"stop":2985.045,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--The facilitation of communication and education seems to me to come within the police power.","start":2985.045,"stop":2990.839,"duration":5.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, then the landlord can buy any sprinkler system he wants to, too.","start":2990.839,"stop":2994.431,"duration":3.59},{"text":"But here you're telling him what one he's going to get.","start":2994.431,"stop":2996.118,"duration":1.69},{"text":"He doesn't have a choice of cable TV operators, does it?","start":2996.118,"stop":3000.461,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that that's only because the city has franchised one company.","start":3000.461,"stop":3005.24,"duration":4.78},{"text":"That's not the result of the tenant.","start":3005.24,"stop":3009.424,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes, but you're attacking an ordinance.","start":3009.424,"stop":3013.533,"duration":4.11},{"text":"You're attacking a law.","start":3013.533,"stop":3016.796,"duration":3.26},{"text":"The city wants to protect its five percent, so it says, please, landlord, you're not going to get a choice of cable operator.","start":3016.796,"stop":3026.934,"duration":10.14}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose they'd get their five percent from whatever cable operators they franchise.","start":3026.934,"stop":3031.885,"duration":4.95},{"text":"I don't think that makes any difference.","start":3031.885,"stop":3033.572,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, the city doesn't need to franchise some of them, because they don't ask for it, as this amicus brief makes clear.","start":3033.572,"stop":3041.942,"duration":8.37}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in addition to fire escapes and sprinklers... in addition to sprinklers, there are fire escapes and smoke detectors, and those have a safety element in it.","start":3041.942,"stop":3052.875,"duration":10.93},{"text":"But let me point out several things.","start":3052.875,"stop":3055.483,"duration":2.61},{"text":"The Causby case has been referred to.","start":3055.483,"stop":3057.608,"duration":2.13},{"text":"We usually think of that as the case which said that when there are low-flying planes that means that is a taking.","start":3057.608,"stop":3063.934,"duration":6.33},{"text":"But the Causby case is the case which, by way of dictum, but it certainly is one of the most powerful dictums that was ever uttered by this Court, said that the statutes of Congress which provide that the upper air space is a public highway and can be used freely without compensation, thereby changing the clear common law, which said from the surface of the earth to the highest heavens, the Court in the Causby case said that property can be taken without compensation.","start":3063.934,"stop":3097.217,"duration":33.28},{"text":"Now, similarly in Block and Hirsch, which is the early rent control case.","start":3097.217,"stop":3104.464,"duration":7.25},{"text":"The statute in that case provides the tenant can continue to occupy the property after the end of the lease if he continues to pay the same rent, and that is surely a permanent occupation.","start":3104.464,"stop":3120.113,"duration":15.65},{"text":"And one that rather appeals to me is mailboxes.","start":3120.113,"stop":3125.69,"duration":5.58},{"text":"We have cited Section 57 of the New York Multiple Dwelling Act.","start":3125.69,"stop":3133.311,"duration":7.62},{"text":"Mr. Gruen in his brief says, well, there isn't any requirement that there be mailboxes.","start":3133.311,"stop":3141.027,"duration":7.72},{"text":"What the situation is is that the Post Office Department, through regulations... and this is... this is 155.6, says that:","start":3141.027,"stop":3164.454,"duration":23.43},{"text":"\"Delivery of mail shall be contingent upon the installation and maintenance of mail receptacles approved by the Postal Service. \"","start":3164.454,"stop":3176.279,"duration":11.82},{"text":"Which would mean that if you don't have the receptacles you don't get mail.","start":3176.279,"stop":3182.291,"duration":6.01},{"text":"But New York has provided by Section 57 that you must provide for receptacles.","start":3182.291,"stop":3188.399,"duration":6.11},{"text":"And let's continue with the Post Office regulations.","start":3188.399,"stop":3192.882,"duration":4.48},{"text":"There is a regulation on apartment house mail receptacles called Publication 17, and it provides on page 12 that mailboxes must be 6 inches by 5 inches by 15 inches.","start":3192.882,"stop":3212.108,"duration":19.23},{"text":"Now, if you multiply that out, it's 450 cubic inches.","start":3212.108,"stop":3216.559,"duration":4.45},{"text":"And if you take a half-inch cable which is on the roof, it takes 194 feet of half-inch cable to occupy 450 cubic inches.","start":3216.559,"stop":3231.554,"duration":14.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, again you're... there it's like the sprinklers.","start":3231.554,"stop":3237.208,"duration":5.65},{"text":"They're the landlord's boxes.","start":3237.208,"stop":3239.238,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"He has to pay for them, yes.","start":3239.238,"stop":3241.236,"duration":2},{"text":"And Mrs. Loretto is better off.","start":3241.236,"stop":3244.454,"duration":3.22},{"text":"She doesn't have to pay for the--","start":3244.454,"stop":3245.891,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I know.","start":3245.891,"stop":3246.188,"duration":0.3},{"text":"But nevertheless, they're a third party coming in and taking a piece of your property or occupying a piece of your property.","start":3246.188,"stop":3257.168,"duration":10.98}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--This is permanent occupation of a part of Mrs. Loretto's property, which she is not free to use for some other purpose.","start":3257.168,"stop":3266.447,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What if New York added Telex to the CATV as a means of communication?","start":3266.447,"stop":3272.975,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the time might come when that would seem to be reasonable.","start":3272.975,"stop":3276.833,"duration":3.86},{"text":"As of now it seems rather far-fetched.","start":3276.833,"stop":3278.973,"duration":2.14},{"text":"But in New York City I suggest that cable television has become as near a necessity as a telephone and electric service, as to which there really isn't any question because they are always provided.","start":3278.973,"stop":3295.794,"duration":16.82},{"text":"And what New York was trying to do through this statute was to facilitate the development of cable service as a means of improving communication and education in the city of New York or the state of New York.","start":3295.794,"stop":3313.053,"duration":17.26},{"text":"And I would suggest that that is within the generally accepted powers of state legislatures.","start":3313.053,"stop":3322.644,"duration":9.59},{"text":"Now, I would like to refer to Penn Central.","start":3322.644,"stop":3324.314,"duration":1.67},{"text":"It's easy to say, well, Penn Central is just regulation.","start":3324.314,"stop":3329.453,"duration":5.14},{"text":"It's not... it doesn't have anything to do with occupation.","start":3329.453,"stop":3332.171,"duration":2.72},{"text":"But the fact was that all that space up there, which was reachable by the Penn Central people by building up it, was taken away from them.","start":3332.171,"stop":3341.604,"duration":9.43},{"text":"It isn't that it is occupied by someone else; it's not occupied by them, which is a complete interference with their rights of ownership.","start":3341.604,"stop":3352.257,"duration":10.65},{"text":"It is true that they received a sort of compensation in the form of transferable development rights.","start":3352.257,"stop":3361.783,"duration":9.53},{"text":"But it is also clear that the Court did not have any conception... or didn't decide that that constituted full value or payment.","start":3361.783,"stop":3371.077,"duration":9.29},{"text":"I would suggest that that is a case of permanent occupancy of the Penn Central space without the payment of just compensation, because the Court concluded on the balance of all the factors involved this was the kind of regulation which did not constitute a taking.","start":3371.077,"stop":3391.552,"duration":20.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that any more permanent occupancy than any zoning ordinance that says you can only use a portion of your property?","start":3391.552,"stop":3397.659,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think I could cite zoning ordinances as another instance.","start":3397.659,"stop":3401.283,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Indeed, this all goes back to Mundt against Illinois, which in 1877 decided that the taking provision of the Fifth Amendment does not prevent... or of the Fourteenth Amendment... does not prevent a state from regulating substantially to the extent of taking away a large share of the profits of a business.","start":3401.283,"stop":3430.989,"duration":29.71},{"text":"Now, we have a number of other instances.","start":3430.989,"stop":3439.08,"duration":8.09},{"text":"The Section 50(c) of the New York Multiple Dwelling Law provides that the landlord must allow the tenants to organize and provide a doorman in the building.","start":3439.08,"stop":3462.086,"duration":23.01},{"text":"The doorman occupies some of the landlord's space, for which he receives no compensation.","start":3462.086,"stop":3470.006,"duration":7.92},{"text":"There is an interesting passage by Mr. Justice Brandeis--","start":3470.006,"stop":3476.065,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a security measure too, I take it, isn't it?","start":3476.065,"stop":3477.658,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"--It's only the... it's only the tenants who do this.","start":3477.658,"stop":3484.719,"duration":7.06},{"text":"The landlord is not required to do it.","start":3484.719,"stop":3487.201,"duration":2.48},{"text":"It has to do with security.","start":3487.201,"stop":3490.887,"duration":3.69},{"text":"But I don't think these things are... certainly Penn Central had nothing to do with security.","start":3490.887,"stop":3496.307,"duration":5.42},{"text":"That related to something else.","start":3496.307,"stop":3499.165,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I think your time has expired now, Mr. Griswold.","start":3499.165,"stop":3501.429,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I just read one quotation from Justice Brandeis?","start":3501.429,"stop":3504.944,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"One quotation, yes.","start":3504.944,"stop":3505.366,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"This is on page 33 of our brief, the Delaware, Lackawanna & Western Railroad.","start":3505.366,"stop":3513.862,"duration":8.5},{"text":"It had to do with a city ordinance providing a taxi stand on railroad land.","start":3513.862,"stop":3519.532,"duration":5.67},{"text":"The Court held that that ordinance was invalid.","start":3519.532,"stop":3523.359,"duration":3.83},{"text":"But Mr. Justice Brandeis said that if","start":3523.359,"stop":3526.483,"duration":3.12},{"text":"\"the town should pass an ordinance establishing, on the driveway, a taxi stand available only to incoming passengers, I see no reason why, under the contract between it and the railroad or under the general laws of New Jersey, it may not do so. \"","start":3526.483,"stop":3545.178,"duration":18.69},{"text":"And we suggest that that is the sort of earmark of a use-dependent regulation, that this regulation here depends upon the use of the property for rental purposes, and that it should be sustained.","start":3545.178,"stop":3561.156,"duration":15.98}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have anything further, Mr. Gruen?","start":3561.156,"stop":3565.811,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Michael S. Gruen","textObjs":[{"text":"If I may for a few minutes.","start":3565.811,"stop":3568.528,"duration":2.72},{"text":"First let me take up a couple of areas where Mr. Griswold and we agree.","start":3568.528,"stop":3574.792,"duration":6.26},{"text":"One is that I also would like to argue the telephone case, but on the other side.","start":3574.792,"stop":3579.585,"duration":4.79},{"text":"The second is more germane to this case.","start":3579.585,"stop":3585.443,"duration":5.86},{"text":"Mr. Griswold has proposed that if trunk lines were installed under the auspices of Section 828 that would probably be unconstitutional, but that he distinguishes between trunk lines and feeder lines.","start":3585.443,"stop":3602.202,"duration":16.76},{"text":"We of course agree that such installation of trunk lines would be unconstitutional, but I think we differ on the facts.","start":3602.202,"stop":3613.464,"duration":11.26},{"text":"Let me demonstrate to you, if you will take a look at joint appendix page 166, just what a crossover is, what a block circuit installation is.","start":3613.464,"stop":3625.816,"duration":12.35},{"text":"This diagram on page 166 illustrates a typical New York City block and a typical installation by Teleprompter.","start":3625.816,"stop":3636.079,"duration":10.26},{"text":"In the upper left-hand corner of the diagram, the cable enters at number 118 Riverside Drive.","start":3636.079,"stop":3643.872,"duration":7.79},{"text":"It then continues about halfway around the block on West 84th Street and it goes down along Riverside Drive from 118 to 110 Riverside Drive, and then along the lower rung of buildings on West 83rd Street, occasionally crossing back to the buildings on 84th Street to provide service there.","start":3643.872,"stop":3668.159,"duration":24.29},{"text":"What this diagram shows is a trunk line, in my opinion, what I would call a trunk line.","start":3668.159,"stop":3678.265,"duration":10.11},{"text":"This diagram shows that the typical installation is the use of rooftops of buildings in New York as if they were a public highway.","start":3678.265,"stop":3689.636,"duration":11.37},{"text":"There is an easement there, by all traditional definitions of what an easement is, to provide service to buildings by dropping feeder lines from that trunks line along the roof to individual apartments and buildings.","start":3689.636,"stop":3705.737,"duration":16.1},{"text":"There has been discussion about the Attorney General providing in New York that a tenant is entitled to receive telephone service if he wants, the telephone company may be required to condemn it.","start":3705.737,"stop":3737.116,"duration":31.38},{"text":"We of course don't deny for a minute that the legislature in New York may require the provision of cable television service.","start":3737.116,"stop":3745.816,"duration":8.7},{"text":"What we say is that, just like in the case of telephone service, it requires condemnation or compensation in the form of rental payments for the use of our property.","start":3745.816,"stop":3757.514,"duration":11.7},{"text":"Mr. Griswold suggested that the labor cases, such as Babcock & Wilcox, allow absolutely free entry by organizers onto private property.","start":3757.514,"stop":3778.661,"duration":21.15},{"text":"I would suggest that this is slightly inaccurate.","start":3778.661,"stop":3781.942,"duration":3.28},{"text":"What these cases provide... particularly I refer you to Central Hardware and Babcock & Wilcox... is that where the owner of the property has situated it in such a way that it's inaccessible... his employees are inaccessible by any means other than a temporary entry by union organizers for the limited duration of an organizational campaign, then he has taken steps which modify his property right to the extent that he is in effect creating a nuisance his injuring outsiders by not permitting their entry for very limited purposes onto his property.","start":3781.942,"stop":3821.049,"duration":39.11},{"text":"I would submit that this is not the case here.","start":3821.049,"stop":3823.658,"duration":2.61},{"text":"There is no necessity.","start":3823.658,"stop":3824.939,"duration":1.28},{"text":"Communications can proceed quite freely to tenants absent cable television, by mail, telephone, any other method.","start":3824.939,"stop":3833.123,"duration":8.18},{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":3833.123,"stop":3834.107,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, gentlemen.","start":3834.107,"stop":3834.56,"duration":0.45},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3834.56,"stop":3835.701,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The honorable Court is now adjourned until tomorrow at 10 o'clock.","start":3835.701,"stop":3841.512,"duration":5.81}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Mar 30, 1982","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"81-244","citation":"458US419(1982)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/458/419","lowerCourt":"New York Court of Appeals","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 30, 1982"}